{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503873"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:08:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:08:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2092"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2092"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.25,0.04,0.38,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2092"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81251"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2092"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2092"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66584"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"593"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27103"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81251"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with lower abdominal pain and vaginal spotting. She is nine weeks pregnant with her first pregnancy. Her menstrual cycles are regular at 28 days. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender, with no signs of peritonism. Speculum examination reveals a closed cervix with a small amount of old blood. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal a serum beta-human chorionic gonadotropin of 6,000 IU/L. Transvaginal ultrasound shows an intrauterine gestational sac 18mm with crown-rump length of 5 mm and no detectable fetal heartbeat.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Suction D\u0026C","Misoprostol","Methotrexate","Repeat ultrasound in 7 days","Repeat ultrasound in 48 hours"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features concerning for early pregnancy loss, but which do not yet meet diagnostic criteria. When the crown-rump length is less than 7mm and no cardiac activity is seen, a repeat ultrasound in 7 days is required to confirm pregnancy failure. This conservative approach prevents inadvertent termination of potentially viable pregnancies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound in 7 days\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. This interval allows sufficient time for a viable pregnancy to demonstrate growth and cardiac activity, while also allowing definitive diagnosis of pregnancy failure if no progression occurs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound in 48 hours\u003C/strong\u003E would be too soon to see meaningful changes in early pregnancy ultrasound findings. A full week is needed to avoid ambiguous results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMisoprostol\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate at this stage as pregnancy failure has not been definitively diagnosed. Medical management should only be initiated once strict diagnostic criteria for pregnancy failure have been met.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuction D\u0026C\u003C/strong\u003E carries the risk of terminating a potentially viable pregnancy and should only be performed once pregnancy failure is confirmed. It would be an option after confirmation of pregnancy failure if the patient prefers surgical management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E is used for ectopic pregnancy management and is contraindicated here as there is a confirmed intrauterine pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrent guidelines emphasise the importance of meeting strict diagnostic criteria before confirming early pregnancy failure. These criteria include: no cardiac activity with crown-rump length \u22657mm, no embryo with mean sac diameter \u226525mm, or no interval growth on repeat scan after 7-14 days.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ultrasound findings must meet strict criteria before diagnosing early pregnancy loss to avoid inadvertent termination of viable pregnancies.","A crown-rump length \u003C7mm without cardiac activity requires repeat ultrasound in 7 days before confirming pregnancy loss.","Serial ultrasounds and quantitative beta-hCG measurements help differentiate between early pregnancy loss and early viable pregnancy."],"references":["Ectopic pregnancy and miscarriage: diagnosis and initial management. In: NICE guideline [NG126] [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng126","The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists. Early Pregnancy Loss. ACOG Practice Bulletin. 2018;132(5):197-206. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30157093/","Bleeding \u0026 Pain in Early Pregnancy. Ectopic Pregnancy, Miscarriage \u0026 PUL. In: South Australian Perinatal Practice Guideline [online]. Available at: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/clinical+resources/clinical+programs+and+practice+guidelines/womens+and+babies+health/perinatal/perinatal+practice+guidelines/perinatal+practice+guidelines"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66584"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2092"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66584"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-25T08:17:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-25T08:21:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2092"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81251"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt